Could we switch back to the other,
please?

00:45:59.480 --> 00:46:05.930
So if we look at how all that is charged,
we have on iMOD something very simple.

00:46:06.160 --> 00:46:08.390
Well, at least in the beginning
it was very simple,

00:46:08.390 --> 00:46:12.960
but it's very hard to live
with it while it evolves.

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:17.090
It is simple in the fact that
we charge one cent by kilobyte.

00:46:17.310 --> 00:46:22.080
So if you just make email, that's right,
because an email is something

00:46:22.110 --> 00:46:25.940
in the kilobyte range,
two or three kilobytes.

00:46:25.940 --> 00:46:33.100
And when you start to download files
that are in the range of 100 kilobytes,

00:46:33.100 --> 00:46:35.960
then it makes you something
like a euro or a dollar,

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:39.000
which is approximately
the same for a video,

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:42.290
and starts to be really expensive.

00:46:42.300 --> 00:46:47.740
And on top of that,
the economic model that the content

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:52.780
provider want to use is the same
as the Ringtone economic model that

00:46:52.780 --> 00:46:54.160
is they want to charge for a video.

00:46:54.160 --> 00:46:59.420
So if you subscribe for a month,
and during that month you

00:46:59.420 --> 00:47:03.730
could get a number of videos,
and at the moment it's in the

00:47:03.730 --> 00:47:06.590
range of two to five videos.

00:47:08.740 --> 00:47:14.800
So I will talk a little
bit about content creation.

00:47:14.980 --> 00:47:18.900
Some consequences of the
file size that we have.

00:47:18.970 --> 00:47:24.190
Since it is very limited,
then we need to work on the video.

00:47:24.250 --> 00:47:29.000
And while it's not our job,
but we have to help the content

00:47:29.090 --> 00:47:31.100
providers to work on that.

00:47:31.180 --> 00:47:36.220
The story about this is, in iMOD,
we have content providers

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:41.150
coming from a reasons that
are very different from video.

00:47:41.150 --> 00:47:45.570
We have people making newspapers,
we have people selling ringtones,

00:47:45.570 --> 00:47:48.820
and all of a sudden they want to
put some video on their websites.

00:47:48.820 --> 00:47:52.180
And we have to tell them, well,
if you want to do so,

00:47:52.180 --> 00:47:56.700
you have to use such tools,
you have to follow such rules, and, well,

00:47:56.810 --> 00:47:59.050
we have to define those rules.

00:47:59.840 --> 00:48:05.930
So video sequence must be very simple,
that is, not too many sinkers.

00:48:06.190 --> 00:48:09.510
There might be a contradiction with
the kind of trailers that we can

00:48:09.510 --> 00:48:13.980
see where everything is going very
fast and in the end you don't see

00:48:13.990 --> 00:48:17.300
anything if you encode it right away.

00:48:17.300 --> 00:48:20.010
We have to also optimize the sound.

00:48:20.010 --> 00:48:24.500
The sound is something very -- to
which the user is very sensitive,

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:25.260
in fact.

00:48:25.400 --> 00:48:30.400
If you put two videos with soundtracks
encoded at different qualities,

00:48:30.400 --> 00:48:35.340
then although they are the same,
the users will prefer the

00:48:35.340 --> 00:48:38.220
one with the best soundtrack.

00:48:38.220 --> 00:48:40.050
So we have to live with that.

00:48:40.090 --> 00:48:41.100
And there are some contents.

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:45.570
For instance, if you have a news,
then someone is speaking,

00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:48.260
you can use without any
problem a voice codec.

00:48:48.330 --> 00:48:52.860
But if you have someone singing,
if I start to sing right now,

00:48:52.860 --> 00:48:54.440
if I want to encode that,
then if I want to encode that,

00:48:54.440 --> 00:48:57.040
if I use an iMarketDec,
it's the end of the world because

00:48:57.040 --> 00:49:01.220
there will be some glitches in the
soundtrack and it's unacceptable.

00:49:01.220 --> 00:49:04.910
So we also have to define
how to encode that.

00:49:05.050 --> 00:49:11.580
And to do so, we have the AAC codec,
which also requires a higher bit wedge.

00:49:11.610 --> 00:49:15.110
So there is a compromise between
the amount of data that you put

00:49:15.130 --> 00:49:18.500
into the audio and the amount
of data you have in the video.

00:49:21.560 --> 00:49:27.880
For the digital right management,
there are several ways to do it.

00:49:27.880 --> 00:49:32.160
At the moment,
the only tool that we have to create

00:49:32.260 --> 00:49:40.610
content and to have the protection is
QuickTime Pro that completely supports

00:49:40.610 --> 00:49:43.640
the file format defined by Entity.como.

00:49:43.650 --> 00:49:50.310
And while it can be seen as a limitation
for certain content providers.

00:49:52.480 --> 00:49:54.400
But it enables the protection.

00:49:54.400 --> 00:50:00.770
If we have a look at different
parameters we can use,

00:50:00.770 --> 00:50:07.400
here there is the different profiles
optimized for duration or video quality.

00:50:07.400 --> 00:50:13.260
And you can see the
video quality and audio.

00:50:15.500 --> 00:50:19.710
I'm looking for the-- OK,
duration is there.

00:50:19.890 --> 00:50:24.720
So if you want a high quality
video that was the parameter

00:50:24.720 --> 00:50:28.650
set for the football sequence,
then you encode at 64 kilobits per

00:50:29.030 --> 00:50:32.120
second with 10 to 15 frames per second.

00:50:32.130 --> 00:50:35.330
That number of frames per second
is largely sufficient due to

00:50:35.330 --> 00:50:38.080
the definition of the image.

00:50:38.080 --> 00:50:45.260
And you can use an IMR codec
or you can not use an ECODEC.

00:50:45.500 --> 00:50:50.250
if you just want to emphasize the action.

00:50:50.470 --> 00:50:54.610
And then if you don't mind that
much about the video or if you

00:50:54.690 --> 00:50:58.010
have something very static like
head and shoulder sequence,

00:50:58.050 --> 00:51:01.390
you can encode the video at 32
kilobits per second and you end up

00:51:01.510 --> 00:51:07.160
with a duration that is twice the
duration of the high quality video.

00:51:09.480 --> 00:51:14.060
If you look how it works in QuickTime,
well, when you export a file,

00:51:14.080 --> 00:51:17.000
you have a source file,
a clean source file in QuickTime.

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:22.670
When you export it to 3GPP file format,
you have different tabs in which you

00:51:22.670 --> 00:51:25.500
can select the format of the file.

00:51:25.500 --> 00:51:27.240
So there it's the mobile MPEG-4.

00:51:27.310 --> 00:51:29.200
It's the format defined by entity.

00:51:29.200 --> 00:51:33.240
It's exactly the same thing as 3GP,
except that there is

00:51:33.240 --> 00:51:34.670
the DRM on top of it.

00:51:34.840 --> 00:51:43.700
You can define the definition,
also if there is a nodule tracker or not.

00:51:43.700 --> 00:51:43.700
And then,

00:51:43.810 --> 00:51:46.720
You specify all your
encoded audio on the video,

00:51:46.760 --> 00:51:50.100
and it's very intuitive to do it.

00:51:50.110 --> 00:51:53.360
So it's a really nice tool.

00:51:55.350 --> 00:51:58.640
Well,
so all that is what can be done today.

00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:01.530
The service has just been launched,
so we don't have any

00:52:01.820 --> 00:52:05.090
figures to provide to say,
well, it works very well,

00:52:05.090 --> 00:52:08.040
or the users are really
satisfied with the quality.

00:52:08.190 --> 00:52:12.690
Still,
we are working to define the service

00:52:12.780 --> 00:52:16.080
we will have in the coming years,
taking into account the

00:52:16.080 --> 00:52:17.520
evolution of the network.

00:52:17.790 --> 00:52:23.740
And that's why I'm talking
about the future trends.

00:52:24.460 --> 00:52:29.090
Concerning the contents,
one big need is the

00:52:29.090 --> 00:52:31.660
improved encoding tools.

00:52:31.710 --> 00:52:37.090
Someone yesterday mentioned the fact
that MPEG-2 is now all standard,

00:52:37.100 --> 00:52:40.840
that improves every day
in coding efficiency.

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:49.010
MPEG-4 has hit the market very recently,
so we evaluated a few tools

00:52:49.010 --> 00:52:53.780
and we have similar results,
but we think it could be really improved

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:56.940
by the use of two-pass encoding,
for instance,

00:52:56.940 --> 00:52:58.680
better analysis of the sequences.

00:52:58.700 --> 00:53:04.610
And also we think that the encoder,
the core of the encoder will also evolve.

00:53:04.900 --> 00:53:07.430
We hope so.

00:53:07.470 --> 00:53:10.140
We hope there will be
a lot of progress done.

00:53:10.520 --> 00:53:16.420
Then we can increase the file
size in order to have longer

00:53:16.420 --> 00:53:19.710
clips or to increase the quality.

00:53:19.730 --> 00:53:23.120
So here there is a trade-off,
what the users in the end want.

00:53:23.120 --> 00:53:30.160
And it's not a very easy question because
depending on how we charge the content,

00:53:30.160 --> 00:53:36.790
what if I charge one euro for ten
seconds of video and if I charge

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:42.410
two euros for ten seconds of video,
but with a file that is twice the size,

00:53:42.410 --> 00:53:46.550
then maybe the users,
although the video quality is better,

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:47.680
they won't understand.

00:53:47.800 --> 00:53:52.510
So we really have a problem
of how to charge the content.

00:53:56.100 --> 00:54:03.420
Then what you saw on the phone is
a phone with a QVGR resolution.

00:54:03.530 --> 00:54:06.840
So you put a QC content on QVGR.

00:54:06.840 --> 00:54:08.040
You can zoom it.

00:54:08.040 --> 00:54:09.250
You can make it full screen.

00:54:09.320 --> 00:54:14.970
But then you have some artifacts
due to the extrapolation.

00:54:15.570 --> 00:54:18.890
One interesting thing would
be to increase the image

00:54:18.930 --> 00:54:22.710
definition in the 3GP file.

00:54:22.760 --> 00:54:26.830
If you do that,
then if you go from QC to QVisio,

00:54:26.830 --> 00:54:31.910
then the surface of the image is doubled,
mostly doubled.

00:54:31.910 --> 00:54:34.440
It means that if you want
to keep the same quality,

00:54:34.440 --> 00:54:36.460
you have to double the file size.

00:54:36.460 --> 00:54:38.570
So it's a never-ending problem.

00:54:38.680 --> 00:54:42.180
Whatever you change,
you have to improve something.

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:45.600
So we can look at the encoding tools.

00:54:45.770 --> 00:54:48.240
We can also look at the codecs.

00:54:48.500 --> 00:54:53.980
There is the H.264 MPEG-4
AVC that is being introduced.

00:54:54.030 --> 00:54:58.410
There has been some
press release and so on.

00:54:58.460 --> 00:55:04.300
We should gain from that
50%. For the same quality,

00:55:04.300 --> 00:55:09.480
we should gain 50%. But we are waiting
for something working for mobile phones,

00:55:09.500 --> 00:55:13.410
because we have the encoder
problem and also the availability

00:55:13.410 --> 00:55:15.850
of colleagues for the phones.

00:55:16.360 --> 00:55:22.800
And then another improvement
could be the use of AAC+, where

00:55:22.840 --> 00:55:27.650
we could achieve higher audio
quality for half the bandwidth.

00:55:27.730 --> 00:55:31.590
So also an improvement we're waiting.

00:55:34.880 --> 00:55:39.180
For the content,
there are two evolutions.

00:55:39.180 --> 00:55:45.990
One is progressive download,
because as mentioned earlier,

00:55:46.500 --> 00:55:49.990
If my file size is too long,
and if I have to wait until the

00:55:49.990 --> 00:55:54.080
end of the file size is downloaded,
then maybe that waiting time

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:56.120
is too long for me and I quit.

00:55:56.220 --> 00:56:00.160
So the idea with progressive download
is to start downloading the file,

00:56:00.460 --> 00:56:03.110
and as soon as there is
enough data into the buffer,

00:56:03.140 --> 00:56:05.080
start playing it.

00:56:05.610 --> 00:56:10.020
So this improves the user
experience with a click and play.

00:56:10.020 --> 00:56:11.630
I click, it plays.

00:56:11.780 --> 00:56:15.350
And it allows encoding of some
contents with higher bitrate than the

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:17.950
available throughput on the network.

00:56:17.960 --> 00:56:22.520
So that's very interesting if we want
to increase the quality of the image.

00:56:23.320 --> 00:56:27.900
Then the other way is to look
at streaming for video on

00:56:27.900 --> 00:56:30.490
demand or for live channels.

00:56:32.100 --> 00:56:39.080
It's possible today,
but one limitation is that if

00:56:39.130 --> 00:56:42.350
we have one user streaming at 40
kilobits per second in a cell,

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:45.170
then it might be the only
GPRS user in the cell.

00:56:45.180 --> 00:56:47.770
So it's a strong

00:56:48.290 --> 00:56:52.620
And it will be possible more
easily when Edge is deployed and,

00:56:52.620 --> 00:56:54.340
of course, UMTS.

00:56:56.610 --> 00:57:02.340
A problem with that is we need to
introduce new elements in the network.

00:57:02.340 --> 00:57:05.150
We need to introduce streaming server.

00:57:05.260 --> 00:57:09.290
We need to define an architecture that is

00:57:09.750 --> 00:57:12.910
That is good, both for us and for
the content providers,

00:57:12.910 --> 00:57:16.930
because there are big content
providers like TV channels.

00:57:16.930 --> 00:57:19.580
They can host streaming at home.

00:57:19.580 --> 00:57:21.490
But there are small content providers.

00:57:21.490 --> 00:57:24.890
We doubt that they will be
able to put the money and the

00:57:24.890 --> 00:57:29.430
knowledge to make the investment
of the money and the knowledge.

00:57:29.460 --> 00:57:30.730
So we have a big problem.

00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:33.820
So that is the where.

00:57:33.950 --> 00:57:36.540
The Omni is also in the range of this.

00:57:36.540 --> 00:57:39.260
It's also the same kind of problem.

00:57:42.500 --> 00:57:46.940
A big argument that is often given,
the argument is, well,

00:57:46.940 --> 00:57:50.060
if you put some streaming,
if you have live streaming,

00:57:50.060 --> 00:57:53.560
it is for specific events
like a football match.

00:57:53.560 --> 00:57:57.630
